  "theory": "When an inductive coil is connected in series with a resistor across an AC supply, it forms a series RL circuit. The total impedance is Z = √(R² + XL²), where XL = ωL = 2πfL is the inductive reactance. The current i(t) lags behind the applied voltage v(t) by a phase angle φ = arctan(XL/R). The voltage drop across the resistor is VR = I×R and is in phase with the current, while the voltage drop across the inductor is VL = I×XL and leads the current by 90 degrees.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "Resistor voltage VR is in phase with circuit current i(t).",
    "Inductor voltage VL leads circuit current i(t) by 90 degrees.",
    "Circuit current lags source voltage V(t) by angle φ.",
    "Impedance Z = √(R² + XL²) — total opposition to current.",
    "Power factor cos φ = R/Z (always lagging)."
  ],
  "useCases": [
    "Analyzing AC motors, chokes, and solenoid coils",
